{
    "analysis": "We used metric.csv to compute global thresholds per component-KPI across the full file (P95/P5 etc.), then filtered metrics to the incident window (2021-03-23 23:00–23:30 CST) and counted anomalies per component-KPI. Results show a concentrated set of high-severity anomalies starting around 23:00–23:01: strong high-side disk I/O and disk throughput spikes across MG01, MG02 and multiple Tomcat nodes, plus sustained anomalies on some MySQL KPIs and a Tomcat threads KPI (Tomcat03 CurrentThreads). Most top anomalies are high-side (IO/CPU/WIO), with a few low-side drops. The anomaly cluster timing (~23:00–23:01) suggests a single incident starting at ~23:00–23:01 that impacted OS disk I/O and propagated to application JVMs and MySQL. However, to localize the root cause component (single failure) we must use traces to find which service is the last faulty service in call chains and confirm whether the problem is primarily node-level (disk I/O) or service-level (Tomcat/MySQL). Traces and logs will disambiguate among same-level faulty components. Next step: perform trace analysis using the same global-threshold-then-window-filter approach on trace.csv limited to the allowed candidate components.",
