{
    "analysis": "We ran metric-based anomaly detection and trace analysis. Metric analysis (global thresholds then window filtering) revealed a cluster of high-side disk I/O and local-disk throughput/RTps anomalies on MG01, MG02 and several Tomcat nodes starting around 2021-03-23 23:00–23:01 CST. Tomcat03 also showed a sustained threads anomaly starting at 23:00. Trace analysis shows large duration spikes involving MG02 and Tomcat03 (e.g., MG02 trace.from_dockerA1.duration_p95 has earliest anomaly at 23:00:00 CST; trace.from_Tomcat03.duration_p95 and trace.to_MG02.duration_p95 show earliest anomalies at ~23:05:00 CST). The timing and pattern indicate an early latency spike in MG02 (first observed at 23:00:00 CST in traces) that correlates with subsequent disk I/O anomalies across MG/Tomcat nodes and application-level thread growth in Tomcat03. This sequence suggests MG02 experienced increased service latency likely caused by elevated disk I/O/disk latency on MG02, which propagated to Tomcat services. error_logs.csv is empty so we must rely on log.csv. To confirm the root cause component and the underlying reason, we should inspect log-derived indicators (log.csv) for MG02 and related nodes (MG01, Tomcat03, Tomcat01/02/04) within the same window to find any log-level anomalies (e.g., error_count, gc pause, or other indicators) that support a disk/IO or resource-pressure root cause.",
